ance system and compromise overall constellation safety.\n*   **AI Compute Hardware Evolution:** For orbital AI compute satellites, retirements may also occur sooner than estimated. As more advanced AI hardware becomes available, older hardware is shifted to lower-intensity workloads and eventually retired via controlled end-of-life disposition (e.g., graveyard orbits) to maintain optimal compute economics.\n\n### 4. Capitalization Policies (Build, Launch, Maintenance & Refurbishment)\n*   **Base Satellite Costs:** The capitalized cost of a satellite includes the costs to build it (parts, labor, and allocated overhead) as well as **capitalized launch costs** incurred by the Space segment to deliver the satellite to orbit (including an allocation of flight vehicle costs).\n*   **Interest Capitalization:** Qualified interest costs incurred during the significant acquisition or construction phase (before the asset is ready for its intended use) are capitalized as part of the asset's historical cost and depreciated over its useful life.\n*   **Maintenance vs. Refurbishment:**\n    *   **Expensed:** Routine expenditures for maintenance and repairs that *do not* extend the life of the asset are expensed as incurred.\n    *   **Capitalized:** Significant refurbishments, renewals, and enhancements that increase the functionality, output, or expected life of an asset are capitalized and depreciated ratably over the identified useful life.",
