        output="Based on the provided financial statement excerpts, here is the comprehensive accounting policy for Property, Plant, and Equipment (PP&E) depreciation, with a specific focus on satellites and aerospace assets:\n\n### 1. General Depreciation Methodology\n*   **Valuation:** PP&E is stated at historical cost less accumulated depreciation.\n*   **Primary Method:** The Company depreciates its assets primarily using the **straight-line method** over their estimated useful lives.\n*   **Leasehold Improvements:** Depreciated over the **shorter** of their estimated useful lives or the related lease term.\n*   **Capitalized Interest:** Interest costs incurred during the construction of significant long-term projects (e.g., AI data centers, launch facilities) are capitalized as part of the asset's historical cost and depreciated over the asset's estimated useful life once placed in service.\n\n### 2. Satellite Depreciation & Capitalization Policy\n*   **Depreciable Base (Cost):** Satellite costs include the costs to build the satellites (parts, labor, and allocated overhead) as well as **capitalized launch costs** incurred by the Space segment to launch them into orbit (which includes an allocation of the flight vehicle's costs).\n*   **Estimated Useful Lives:** \n    *   **Broadband satellites:** 5 years\n    *   **First-generation mobile satellites:** 3 years\n    *   *(General classification table lists Satellites as 3 - 5 years)*\n*   **Factors Considered for Useful Life Estimation:** Management estimates satellite useful lives based on engineering studies, historical on-orbit performance, propellant life, utilization patterns, orbit-raise timing, expected service capability, design enhancements across generations, the evolution of constellation density and technology, and planned transitions to newer satellite technology.\n*   **Sensitivity:** A change in the average useful life of satellite assets by just one year would have a highly material impact on operating income (e.g., an estimated ~$480 million impact for the full year 2025).\n\n### 3. Flight Vehicle & Spacecraft Depreciation (Exception to Straight-Line)\n*   **Depreciation Method:** Unlike other PP&E, reusable flight vehicles and spacecraft (e.g., boosters, fairings, Merlin engines, Dragon capsules) are **not** depreciated using the straight-line method. Instead, they are depreciated based on the **expected number of average flights** for each vehicle.\n*   **Estimated Useful Life:** 5 to 25 flights.\n*   **Factors Considered for Flight Estimation:** \n    1. Continued ability to successfully recover and refurbish the hardware.\n    2. Economic feasibility of incremental flights (supported by declining refurbishment costs).\n    3. Customer acceptance limits for reflown hardware.\n    4. Expected future launches in the mission manifest.\n    5. Anticipated retirement timing of older models (e.g., Falcon) due to transitions to new vehicles (e.g., Starship).\n\n### 4. Estimated Useful Lives of Other PP&E\n| Classification | Estimated Useful Life |\n| :--- | :--- |\n| **Servers and networking equipment** | 5 - 6 years |\n| **Machinery and equipment** | 3 - 10 years |\n| **Data center infrastructure** | 20 - 25 years |\n| **Launch sites** | 7 - 20 years |\n| **Buildings and improvements** | 30 years |\n| **Leasehold improvements** | Shorter of 7 - 20 years or the life of the lease |\n\n### 5. Maintenance, Refurbishment, and Enhancements\n*   **Expensed:** Routine expenditures for maintenance and repairs that do not extend the lives of the assets are expensed as incurred. Routine asset disposals, scrapping, and gateway decommissions are charged to Cost of Revenue or SG&A.\n*   **Capitalized:** Significant refurbishments, renewals, and enhancements that increase the functionality, output, or expected life of an asset are capitalized and depreciated ratably over the identified useful life.\n\n### 6. Changes in Accounting Estimates & Impairment\n*   **Revisions to Useful Lives:** Management periodically reviews useful life and average flight estimates with engineering and operations teams. If it is determined that the useful lives or expected remaining flights are shorter or longer than originally estimated, the Company **adjusts the rate of depreciation** prospectively to reflect the revised estimates.\n*   **Impairment Evaluation:** PP&E is evaluated for impairment at the lowest level of identifiable, independent cash flows whenever events or circumstances indicate the carrying value may not be recoverable (e.g., technological obsolescence, damaged flight vehicles, abandoned production lines). If future cash flows are less than the carrying value, an impairment charge is recognized to write the asset down to its estimated fair value.",
